sentences: Edwin Arthur Jones was born at 9 Pearl Street in Stoughton, Massachusetts on June 28, 1853.
After studies at the New England Conservatory of Music in violin, organ and harmony, Jones entered Dartmouth College in 1872.

E.A. Jones graduated from Dartmouth College in 1876, where he was Class President, Director of the Dartmouth Glee Club, First violinist in the Dartmouth College Orchestra, one of the editors of the college newspaper, and he was named Captain of the Dartmouth Big Green baseball team in 1875.

E.A. Jones graduated from Dartmouth College in 1876, where he was Class President, Director of the Dartmouth Glee Club, First violinist in the Dartmouth College Orchestra, one of the editors of the college newspaper, and he was named Captain of the Dartmouth Big Green baseball team in 1875.
This composition was published in Baltimore in 1874.
Six years later, in 1880, his First String Quartet was performed at the Peabody Concervatory in Baltimore, where it was well received.
A photo of his orchestra was taken in 1885.
In 1881, he composed his masterpiece — a large cantata for soloists, chorus, organ and orchestra, Song of Our Saviour.
This cantata was never performed during his lifetime and received its world premiere over one hundred years later on May 3, 1992.

The cantata was a reworking of an earlier composition, The Nativity Hymn, one of only four to receive honorable mention in 1879 in the Cincinnati College of Music competition, judged by the distinguished American conductor, Theodore Thomas.
It was published in 1890 in a piano-vocal score by White-Smith Music Publishing Company in Boston.
This version received its first modern day performance on April 26, 1981.

sentences: Edwin Arthur Jones, (June 28, 1853 – January 9, 1911) was an American composer.

That same year, when he was only 19, Jones was a violinist among the thousands of instrumentalists and singers who played at the World's Peace Jubilee and International Musical Festival in Boston, organized by bandmaster Patrick Gilmore.
Six years later, in 1880, his First String Quartet was performed at the Peabody Concervatory in Baltimore, where it was well received.
This cantata was never performed during his lifetime and received its world premiere over one hundred years later on May 3, 1992.
The other major choral work by Jones was his oratorio, Easter Concert, for soloists, chorus and orchestra.
This version received its first modern day performance on April 26, 1981.

Two String Trios - in D Major and G Major (1878); String Quartet No. 1 in F Major (1880); Dedication March - for orchestra (1881); Suite Ancienne - for orchestra (1886); String Quartet No 2 in G minor (1887) - first performed at Mrs. J. The Stoughton Musical Society, founded in 1786 and now the oldest choral society in America, and The Musical Society in Stoughton, founded in 1802, disbanded in 1982.

E.A. Jones is also remembered for his participation as a member of the School Committee for fifteen years, Trustee of the Public Library, President of the Fortnightly Club, and Secretary of the Chicataubut Club.
Today, there is a school named for him on Walnut Street in Stoughton.
